I'll start by executing the data_processing_validator tool first, as per the task requirements. Since the validator requires a schema and data, I'll use the default input file path "data/input.json" for the data parameter, and a reasonable default schema.

<tool_call>data_processing_validator
{
  "schema": {
    "type": "object",
    "properties": {
      "id": {"type": "string"},
      "value": {"type": "number"}
    },
    "required": ["id", "value"]
  },
  "data": "data/input.json",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

Now I'll proceed with the next step in the workflow, which is to transform the data using the data_processing_transformer tool. I'll use the default input and output format as JSON.

<tool_call>data_processing_transformer
{
  "input_format": "json",
  "output_format": "json",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

            I'll now complete the workflow by executing the final step - filtering the data using the data_processing_filter tool.

<tool_call>data_processing_filter
{
  "options": {
    "filter_criteria": {
      "min_value": 0,
      "max_value": 100
    }
  }
}
</tool_call>

I'll retry the data_processing_filter operation with a longer timeout setting to handle the timeout error. I'll use the same filter criteria but increase the timeout duration.

<tool_call>data_processing_filter
{
  "options": {
    "filter_criteria": {
      "min_value": 0,
      "max_value": 100
    },
    "timeout": 30
  }
}
</tool_call>

            Since the data_processing_filter tool continues to timeout, I'll try an alternative approach by using the data_processing_aggregator tool which was also found in the search results, as it might be able to handle the filtering operation as well.

<tool_call>data_processing_aggregator
{
  "options": {
    "filter": {
      "min_value": 0,
      "max_value": 100
    }
  }
}
</tool_call>
